To characterize the LLZO electrolyte before cycling, electron microscopy was conducted (Fig. 2
                        ). An SEM micrograph of a polished surface is shown in Fig. 2(a), where no cracks, except a few pores, were observed and was consistent with the expected high relative density of 97±1% [10]. Fig. 2(b) presents a freshly cleaved surface, from which the average grain size is estimated to be ∼2.8±0.8
                        μm, consistent with that reported by previous investigations [14,15]. The fracture mode was predominantly transgranular, indicating relatively high grain boundary strength. A high-resolution transmission electron microscopy (HR-TEM) image of the LLZO (011) plane along the [100] direction is depicted in Fig. 2(c) (the inset is the corresponding selected area electron diffraction pattern). The TEM analysis indicates that the Al-doped LLZO has a cubic crystal structure with a lattice parameter of approximately 1.3nm, which is in agreement with X-ray diffraction (XRD) [10,16].
